  "prompt": "What is the electric potential at the centre of sphere?",
  "response": "The electric potential at the center of a uniformly charged sphere can be calculated using principles from electrostatics. If the sphere has a total charge \\( Q \\) and radius \\( R \\), the electric potential \\( V \\) at the center of the sphere is given by the formula:\n\n\\[ V = \\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\epsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{R} \\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( \\epsilon_0 \\) is the permittivity of free space, approximately \\( 8.85 \\times 10^{-12} \\, \\text{F/m} \\).\n\nThe derivation of this formula involves integrating the contributions of each infinitesimal charge element over the volume of the sphere to determine the total potential at the center. This formula implies that the potential is directly proportional to the total charge and inversely proportional to the radius of the sphere.",
